. Fill in the token details
Note: give it a clear label, e.g. n8n-bot-pr-author — this just helps you identify it later in the token list, it has no functional effect
Expiration: choose a duration — 30 or 90 days is reasonable for testing; you can also pick "No expiration" but GitHub will nag you about it being less secure. For a workflow you'll keep running long-term, 90 days with a calendar reminder to rotate is a good middle ground
Select scopes: this is the important part. Check the box next to:
✅ repo (this is the top-level checkbox — checking it automatically includes all its sub-scopes: repo:status, repo_deployment, public_repo, repo:invite, security_events)
You don't need any other scopes (like admin:org or workflow) for this use case — just repo gives the bot enough access to clone, push, and open pull requests.
5. Generate and copy
Scroll down, click Generate token
GitHub will show the token exactly once, in a green box, starting with ghp_...
Copy it immediately and paste it somewhere safe temporarily (a password manager, or a local note you'll delete after pasting it into n8n/your terminal). If you navigate away or refresh without copying it, you cannot retrieve it again — you'd have to generate a new one.
